Marshfield Schools
September 10 at 1:59 PM ·

All Marshfield R-I students will begin receiving FREE breakfast and lunch beginning on Friday 9/11 due to a USDA waiver.

The USDA Federal Summer Food Service Program has been extended through December 30 or until federal money is no longer available. Our school district is thankful to be able to offer this program as allowed by the Department of Health and Senior Services and USDA for our students and families.

Any lunch money already paid for meal accounts will remain on the student's account for when this program is discontinued.

Even though meals are free, it is very important that families turn in completed Free and Reduced Lunch forms for this school year. These forms are necessary for our school to continue to qualify for many of our meal programs, including Summer Food Service Program and and our free after school super snack program.
#MJaysConquer

post_text:
September 4, 2020
Dear Private/Parochial/Homeschool Provider:
A meeting will be held with representatives of private schools including home schools that serve students with
disabilities residing within the Marshfield R-1 School District. The Marshfield Board of Education made a
policy decision that we will provide services equivalent to the “proportionate share” calculation for those
disabled students.
This meeting will be held for the purpose of consultation. This consultation will include such topics as the
child find process, proportionate share, the provision of special education and related services that will be
provided, and annual count. Evaluation of the services will also need to be addressed.
This meeting will be held on Thursday, October 1, 2020 via Google Meet (https://meet.google.com/jxq-buurkkq). I will be available to answer questions from 8:30 a.m. to 9:30 a.m. through the link. If you have any
questions, please feel free to contact Melynda Van Note, Director of Special Services.
Sincerely,
Melynda Van Note
Melynda Van Note
Director of Special Services

shared_text:
Marshfield Schools
August 28 at 4:03 PM ·

We hate to sound cliché, but we are so thankful to be “BACK IN THE SADDLE”! The events that started last March have been a real “BEE IN OUR BONNET”. At times, it has been an “UPHILL BATTLE”. However, Bluejays are “ALL FOR ONE AND ONE FOR ALL”. We knew that “EVERY CLOUD HAS ITS SILVER LINING” and so we “PUT THE PEDAL TO THE METAL”. They say, “ABSENCE MAKES THE HEART GROW FONDER”, and no doubt that is true. Students are the “APPLE OF OUR EYE”, and we sure did miss them. We spent the summer getting our “DUCKS IN A ROW”, “IRONING OUT THE KINKS”, “WORKING ALL THE BUGS OUT” and “FINE TUNING” this Bluejay Machine. You can “BET YOUR BOTTOM DOLLAR” that we have heard and appreciated the encouragement of our families. While this year has been a “HORSE OF A DIFFERENT COLOR”, we are so thankful for the wonderful week #1 in Bluejay Country! #MJaysConquer

July 14, 2020

Blue Jay Families,

I wanted to share a brief update on the positive COVID case announced yesterday evening involving a K-5 summer school instructor. After consulting further with the health department, we have been informed that the individual is experiencing mild symptoms. Because of this, the students in that classroom will be under a health department quarantine. All families have been notified of this by the school district, so if you have not received a call your child is not affected.

We will continue to work with the Webster County Health Unit to keep our students and staff healthy.

Sincerely,

David Steward, Superintendent

IMPORTANT REMINDER of information previously sent out in the MJays Message in regard to school transportation:
Students may only travel to permanent addresses listed during online registration. There will be NO after school notes accepted for students traveling to addresses parents have not previously listed for their child during online registration. If you would like to list an address in case of emergency after school, please do so during online registration under "PM2 Address." Rather than listing days of the week, you will list "OCCAS." In the event that your student needs to travel to that address, you will either send a note to school with your child or call the building office. Online registration must be complete by August 1st in order to have bus transportation during the first week of school.

8th Grade and 12th Grade Students
Do you have an incoming 8th grade or 12th grade student and need to supply an updated shot record? You can upload the student vaccination during online registration. This ONLY needs to be done if you have NEW immunization information to share with our nursing staff. If your student has an immunization exemption card, the original MUST be turned in. It is not to be uploaded.

post_text: Parents of incoming Kindergarten students, have you completed online registration? Keep these items in mind. Immunization records, birth certificates, proof of residency (if you already have students enrolled in the district and you have not moved, we DO NOT need proof of residency) and parenting plans can be uploaded during online registration. Incoming Kindergarten students are required to have all Kindergarten immunizations completed prior to the first day of school. If your student has an immunization exemption card, the original MUST be turned in. It is not to be uploaded.

You can upload proof of residency during online registration. Your new address will not be updated until proof of residency has been provided. (PROOF OF ADDRESS NOT REQUIRED IF YOU HAVE NOT MOVED)
*Do you have an incoming 8th grade or 12th grade student and need to supply an updated shot record? You can upload the student vaccination during online registration. This ONLY needs to be done if you have NEW immunization information to share with our nursing staff.
*Kindergarten Students - Immunization records, birth certificates, proof of residency and parenting plans can be uploaded during online registration. Incoming Kindergarten students are required to have all Kindergarten immunizations completed prior to the first day of school. If your student has an immunization exemption card, the original MUST be turned in. It is not to be uploaded.

post_text:
Parents,

Our deadline to register for summer school is this Friday, May 15th! We are encouraging all families to sign up this year for at least one session of summer school. With the COVID-19 closure, we believe any opportunity to address learning gaps that may have been created during this time is invaluable. Teachers are designing fun and engaging courses which specifically target learning missed during our closure. It is certain to be an excellent experience for our students. Please consider signing up!

Marshfield High School Counseling Department
April 20 at 2:18 PM ·

Seniors and senior parents...
Good Afternoon Class of 2020,

FYI: Some seniors have money left in their meal accounts. We are going to reimburse that money to those seniors when they pick up their diplomas. If you would prefer to have the funds transferred to a younger siblings' meal accounts instead of getting reimbursed, please contact Jennie Ruth at Central Office.

Jennie Ruth's contact information is jennie.ruth@mjays.us.

Please contact her by May 10th to make this transfer, otherwise, you will automatically receive the funds in cash in an envelope with your diploma. The pickup date for diplomas has not been established. Please continue to check your email for updated information.

Thanks!

Katie Pritchard is with Jason Wilson and Missy Clark.
April 13 at 7:34 PM ·

Today the team drove by to see their favorite student manager and give him his letterman jacket. The girls raised the money to buy the jacket as a way to show Ethan how much he means to them! I want to give a special shoutout to Jason Wilson for taking Ethan under his wing and showing him endless love and encouragement.

Coach Wilson said it best, “I believe Ethan taught us all a lesson. Just live life to the fullest and have fun. Always keep shooting away.” 💙

shared_text:
Injury Prevention at CoxHealth
March 30 at 10:49 AM ·

Win a Free Bicycle & Helmet!!

CoxHealth Trauma Services wants to give the kids in our community a brand new bicycle; all you guys have to do is be kind!

Even with our current community restrictions, we can still go outside and get fresh air and a new bike is just what you need! All you have to do is send us a short video showing us your random acts of kindness or how you can make the world a better, safer, or happier place to be.

We are currently accepting video entries from children 15 and under (with parent supervision) in our area. Videos and applicant info must be submitted by 5/1/20 for a chance to win. Parents, email your children’s Name, Age, School, and your Video to marti.miller@coxhealth.com or submit to the “Injury Prevention at CoxHealth” Facebook page for entry; you will receive a submission confirmation email.

Be Safe and Have fun! We cannot wait to see what you submit.

post_text: Good morning, this is Superintendent David Steward, with updated information related to our current school closure due to the COVID-19 virus. After consulting with other area districts and governmental agencies, Marshfield R-1 is extending the current school closure through April 24, 2020. Extra and co-curricular activities continue to be cancelled throughout the duration of the closure. Meal service will continue to be provided in the same manner that it has been being operated this week. As has been our goal from the beginning of this unprecedented time, our focus is on doing everything we can to protect the health and well-being of those in our community. Repeating, Marshfield R-1 Schools will remain closed through April 24 in an effort to prevent the spread of the COVID-19 virus. Please look for additional details about the extended closure later today. Please stay safe and have a good day.

shared_text:
Marshfield Mo Jr High
March 10 at 10:36 AM ·

Marshfield School District is proud to support Bluejays Michaela Bledsoe (Junior), Vanessa Lampley (Junior), and Chandler Zimmerman (Senior) as they participate in a program called Students of the Year. https://studentsoftheyear.org/
https://events.lls.org/gat/springsoy20/tbeimakkus

This program is through the Leukemia & Lymphoma Society and they are working as a team (Team Beimakkusu) to raise money for the organization. They would like to reach out to the community to ask for support with their goal of raising $10,000.

If our Bluejays are able to raise the most money, they will earn a $5000 scholarship! There will be an award ceremony on April 23 to recognize all the teams in the program. We are very excited to help support these students in this unique leadership building program. Please see the attached letter.

Let's join together as a community and show them that we are Marshfield Strong! #MJaysUnited

The soft lock down in place at Hubble Elementary, Webster Elementary, and Marshfield Junior High has been lifted as of 1:25 PM. Operations at these buildings is now back to normal.

Thanks again to local law enforcement for their partnership as we all work to keep our students safe.

Have a great weekend,

David Steward, Superintendent

The soft lock down in place at Hubble Elementary, Webster Elementary, and Marshfield Junior High has been lifted as of 1:25 PM. Operations at these buildings is now back to normal.

Thanks again to local law enforcement for their partnership as we all work to keep our students safe.

post_text:
At the request of law enforcement, Hubble Elementary, Webster Elementary, and Marshfield Junior High have been placed on a soft lock down. Law enforcement officials are searching for a person of interest in that area of town. This soft lock down has been implemented out of an abundance of caution.

A soft lock down means that students and staff may continue normal movement within the building, but no one may enter or leave the building. We will let you know when this soft lock down is lifted.

The safety and security of our students and staff are, and will continue to be, a top priority for our district. We appreciate that local law enforcement share this priority as well.

David Steward, Superintendent

Marshfield High School Counseling Department
January 7 at 11:13 PM ·

The next ACT exam will be on Saturday, February 8, 2020. If you are planning to take the test, the last day to register (without an additional $30 fee) is this Friday, January 10, 2020.

If you qualify for free or reduced lunch you have two ACT fee waivers available to cover the registration fee. If you are not on free/reduced lunch, Marshfield has funds to cover ONE ACT test during your high school career.

If you need help registering, please email Ms. Gonzales at Nikki.Gonzales@mjays.us

shared_text:
Marshfield High School Counseling Department
December 17, 2019 at 9:40 PM ·

Good evening!
1st semester finals were scheduled for this Thursday and Friday, with a review session to be held tomorrow to help students prepare. Obviously, Mother Nature had other ideas, so we have to modify our plans. We want to be fair and make decisions that are in the best educational interest of our students. With that in mind, Mr. Curley has asked teachers to make modifications to finals, which may include reducing the content on the final or forgoing a final altogether so that students can finish papers/projects/presentations. Students should monitor their email and/or Google classroom accounts over the next day, as teachers MAY be emailing classes with more detailed information.

Enjoy what we HOPE is the last snow day this semester!

Link to finals schedule here: https://docs.google.com/…/1a1Xwm3K-0ulRSlOA9p1ESqpHn3…/edit…

post_text:
We are tickled pink to see all of our students again tomorrow and that's no hogwash! If the kiddos are getting bored, try one of these ideas today...
*Write an actual letter to a relative near or far. It is sure to bring a smile to their face. It's also an excellent opportunity for your kiddo to learn to address an envelope.
*Find an age appropriate recipe and create a family meal together. Maybe even learn to set the table.
*Play a game of checkers. Even the youngest of Bluejays can learn to play this game. Maybe even a checker tournament among siblings?
*Encourage your child to make a list of things they would like to give a try in 2020.
Whatever you do today, enjoy! See you in the morning Bluejays!

post_text:
Are you looking for some snow day fun? Are your kiddos the perfect age to help in the kitchen? Here is a perfect cold day easy recipe for you and your young chef to give a try. Bonus: Dinner for under $10 :)

1 – lb. Ground Beef (brown beef along with diced onion if you choose.) Season meat while browning.
Add the following ingredients and simmer OR transfer meat and following ingredients to a crock pot on low.
4 - Cans of Chili Beans
1 - 15 oz can of Tomato Sauce
1 – can of Rotel

ENJOY!!!

post_text: Many Bluejays have served our country with honor! Are you looking for a way to thank a veteran? Military.com offers up some great ideas like, donating frequent flyer miles, donating time to a veterans group, inviting a veteran as a guest speaker, hiring a veteran and making a donation to a veterans organization. Of course, a sincere thank you is ALWAYS appreciated as well. Happy Veterans Day! #MJaysUnited

shared_text:
Marshfield Bluejays Activities
September 21, 2019 at 1:48 PM ·

The Volleyball Jays are in action in Camdenton today. Lady Jays take the first match 25-16, 25-13 against Battle. The attack was led by B. Crawford with 8 kills and A. Crider with 8 digs.
Lady Jays drop both sets to to Camdentons 25-13, 25-21. A. Crider led the fight with 6 kills and 6 digs.
Lady Jays play big in a tough match against an aggressive Branson team. Picking up two sets 25-22, 26-24. A.Crider with 7 kills, A. Gray 4 digs, and B. Utecht 4 blocks. #bluejaypride
